data.name: Quick Sort
data.description:
Somehow you seem to have altered your NodeJS installation, and now Array.prototype.sort doesn't accept any arguments!

Now this happens:

```javascript
console.log([11, 2, 9, 4, 6, 7, 5, 8, 3, 10, 1].sort()) // [ 1, 10, 11, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9 ]
console.log([11, 2, 9, 4, 6, 7, 5, 8, 3, 10, 1].sort((a, b) => a - b)) // [ 1, 10, 11, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9 ] !!!
```

This is obviously a big problem, as you have tons of unsorted numerical data and you need it sorted, quickly!

Override Array.prototype.sort so that it sorts an array of numbers in ascending order.
Your implementation of `Array.prototype.sort` does not need to accept any arguments (such as a comparison function).

Resolve the crisis you find yourself in!
